bug.short_desc: Opera 11 automatically scrolls unnecessarily when selection a radiobutton

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 860 operaScrollProblem.PNG
When our web application runs in the Opera 11 browser, the page automatically scrolls unnecessarily when a different radiobutton is selected. Opera 11 automatically scrolls the radiobutton to the top of the scroll area, even if the selected radiobutton is already visible. This behavious is visualized in the attached image operaScrollProblem.PNG.
This kind of scrolling is bad. Because if the user selects the second radio button, the first radio button gets automatically scrolled out of the view.
This behaviour only occurs in Opera 11, but not in other browsers like the Internet Explorer or Firefox.
This problem is reproducable with a stand-alone qooxdoo application, see attachment operascrolldemo.zip.
Thanks for the report and the demo.

This is rather strange.
The scroll action can be tracked back to the Focus event handler. More precisely, the __onNativeMouseDown handler for Opera prevents the default of the mousedown event for non-selectable elements. The element in this case is a RadioButton content element with qxSelectable=off and a parent with tabindex=1, in other words focusable but not selectable. For reasons unknown, preventing the default of the mousedown event causes Opera to scroll the button into view on mouseup and (consequently) the ScrollPane container to receive a native scroll event. This is confirmed by the fact that commenting qx.bom.Event.preventDefault(domEvent) "fixes" the issue.
I was unable to reproduce the behaviour reported with Plain HTML & JavaScript, not even with the relevant parts of the element tree copied & pasted. Unfortunately the code does not contain comments that explain why the default action is prevented and neither do the SVN comments contain any hint.
Opera – at least recent versions – does not decorate a selectable "plain" element (tabindex=1) when selected. Therefore it might be an option to remove the code in question, but more research is probably advisable.

According to this example, it does not seem to be a browser bug:
http://pastie.org/private/gj0fx6kvbp1vgirzvyc0kq
I should add that the scroll action on mouseup is independent of the __onNativeMouseUp handler. Commented the native listener for mouseup in _initObserver to confirm.

Turned out this issue is related to a browser bug found in Opera 11. See bug 4543 for more details.
Fixed with r24524 on trunk and r24525 on branch_1_3_x.
I provided a work-around by preventing the default of the mousedown event only in older versions of Opera. This has the downside that text selection is possible in Opera 11, however IMHO this is not as disruptive as the automatic scrolling described.
Cannot scroll in SelectBox and ComboBox, since the box is hidden on click.
Fixed with r25138 on trunk and r25141 on branch_1_3_x.

In contrast to the first fix, the second fix mentioned above does not break scrolling in ComboBox and SelectBox. However, it turns out that not only clicking can cause the unexpected scroll (fixed) but also focusing with the tab key or programmatically triggering a focus (e.g. by setting the RadioButton's value to true).
It boils down to the DOM focus method called in qx.event.handler.Focus#focus. As soon as this method is called, Opera scrolls the element the method was applied on into view. The scrolling even happens before the DOMFocusIn event is fired.
It is unclear why accepting the default of the "mousedown" event does circumvent the scrolling operation. It may be part of a more general patch to understand this. In the simple example attached to the related browser bug 4543 clicking on the first element (labeled "focus on mousedown") causes the browser to scroll. Interestingly, the listener does not prevent the default (accepting the default action), thus mimicking the behaviour found in qooxdoo. One would therefore expect no scrolling.

Our problem is solved with the update to the new version 11.10Beta of opera (and probably also due to your fixes r24524 and r25138). From my point of view, you could close this case. But I leave this issue open in case you want to check if your implemented fixed/workarounds are still needed with the new (fixed) version of opera.

Closing this bug since
- clicking does no longer trigger scrolling (in all versions of Opera) thanks to fix - focusing only triggers scrolling in Opera 11.0x, fixed in Opera 11.1x
Fixed with r25146 on trunk and r24525 on branch_1_3_x.
Do not apply fix for Opera >= 11.10. This fix has side effects (non-selectable text being selectable).
Fixed with r26184 on trunk and r26185 on branch_1_3_x.
Unfortunately, we were forced to revert the work around because it was breaking a number of things (context menu, text selection possible).
